e understood and navigated their world, from travel through the countryside and encounters with demons to philosophical medicine and the etiquette of imperial courts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCivilization, Ancient. 0aCivilization, Classical. 0aIntellectual lifexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aancient civilization.  aancient people.  acognitive science.  acultural history.  aepistemology.  ahistorical knowledge.  ahistorical thought.  ahistory of epistemology.  ahistory of science.  ahistory of theology.  ahistory of thought.  aimperial courts.  aintellectual history.  aknowing in ancient civilization.  aknowledge.  alate antiquity.  anature of cognition.  aphilosophical medicine.  apolitical history.  apost structuralism.  apost structuralist theory.  aproblems of knowledge.  asocial history.  atheories of knowledge.1 aAyres, Lewis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalberg, Mira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerkowitz, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanepa, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChin, Catherine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChin, Catherine Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGleason, Maud W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrey, Cam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKalleres, Dayna S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKulikowski, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarx-Wolf, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator